---
description: Svelte/Tauri frontend standards for the ClinSize desktop app
globs: apps/desktop/src/**/*.svelte,apps/desktop/src/**/*.ts
alwaysApply: false
---

Full detail: `handbook/05-svelte-tauri-standards.md`, `handbook/06-ui-ux-guidelines.md`.

- SvelteKit renders forms, results, warnings, and charts. It never implements
  a statistical formula — that always lives in `clinsize-core`.
- TypeScript may validate for UX (instant feedback, disabling a button), but
  Rust validation is authoritative. Never assume the UI already prevented an
  invalid Tauri command call.
- Keep TypeScript DTOs (in `src/lib/types` or similar) structurally aligned
  with the matching Rust struct. If a Rust DTO's fields change, update the
  TypeScript type in the same change.
- Use local component state for a single form/page. Reach for a shared
  Svelte store only for things that outlive one page: selected method, user
  preferences, recent calculations, theme.
- Visual style is a restrained professional workbench, not a marketing page:
  neutral background, compact panels, tables for comparison, minimal
  decoration. No hero sections, oversized cards, or decorative gradients.
- Every calculation method screen needs: method + endpoint context, solve
  mode selector, inputs grouped by clinical meaning, inline validation,
  result summary (primary output, group sizes, total N, achieved power,
  effect size), assumptions and warnings (visible, not buried), a
  sensitivity view, and an export action.
- Use clinical terminology as written in the handbook (treatment/control
  group, allocation ratio, superiority/non-inferiority/equivalence, dropout,
  achieved power, Type I error) — not casual paraphrases.
- Don't assume path separators, a default documents folder, or macOS-only
  keyboard labels. Use Tauri's dialog/filesystem APIs.
